WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:02.670
Welcome to the final tutorial!

00:00:02.670 --> 00:00:05.341
Let's make sure you never run out of

00:00:05.341 --> 00:00:06.009
disk again.

00:00:06.009 --> 00:00:08.013
We'll grow a full repository online,

00:00:08.013 --> 00:00:10.350
hand deleted space back to the pool,

00:00:10.350 --> 00:00:13.022
and then teach the machine to do both

00:00:13.022 --> 00:00:13.356
automatically.

00:00:14.130 --> 00:00:15.404
Here's the model.

00:00:15.404 --> 00:00:17.952
Every repository is a file in

00:00:17.952 --> 00:00:19.650
one shared datastore pool.

00:00:19.650 --> 00:00:22.198
Repositories can grow online while the

00:00:22.198 --> 00:00:23.472
containers keep running.

00:00:23.472 --> 00:00:26.020
But deleting data inside a repo

00:00:26.020 --> 00:00:27.718
frees nothing by itself.

00:00:27.718 --> 00:00:30.266
Trim is what hands the blocks

00:00:30.266 --> 00:00:31.964
back to the pool.

00:00:31.964 --> 00:00:34.088
And a policy automates both.

00:00:37.352 --> 00:00:39.925
Fill the repository most of the way

00:00:39.925 --> 00:00:40.660
and check:

00:00:40.660 --> 00:00:42.498
the filesystem is getting tight.

00:00:48.126 --> 00:00:49.035
Nearly full.

00:00:49.035 --> 00:00:50.399
Time to grow.

00:00:53.677 --> 00:00:54.943
Grow it online.

00:00:54.943 --> 00:00:57.474
The encrypted container and the filesystem

00:00:57.474 --> 00:01:00.005
expand while the containers keep running

00:01:00.005 --> 00:01:01.271
— zero downtime,

00:01:01.271 --> 00:01:02.115
zero unmount.

00:01:05.115 --> 00:01:06.619
Four gigabytes now.

00:01:06.619 --> 00:01:07.622
Nothing restarted.

00:01:10.918 --> 00:01:12.162
Verify from inside:

00:01:12.162 --> 00:01:12.991
same volume,

00:01:12.991 --> 00:01:14.236
double the room.

00:01:18.848 --> 00:01:20.075
The app never noticed.

00:01:23.365 --> 00:01:24.851
Now the other direction.

00:01:24.851 --> 00:01:27.452
Delete the big file — but watch:

00:01:27.452 --> 00:01:30.052
the pool does not get the space

00:01:30.052 --> 00:01:30.795
back yet.

00:01:30.795 --> 00:01:33.396
Deleted blocks stay reserved inside the image.

00:01:35.146 --> 00:01:36.261
Freed inside the repo,

00:01:36.261 --> 00:01:37.654
still owned by the image.

00:01:40.989 --> 00:01:43.538
Trim hands those blocks back to the

00:01:43.538 --> 00:01:44.267
datastore pool,

00:01:44.267 --> 00:01:44.631
online.

00:01:44.631 --> 00:01:47.180
This is the step most setups forget.

00:01:50.180 --> 00:01:50.585
Reclaimed.

00:01:50.585 --> 00:01:52.609
The pool can breathe again.

00:01:55.927 --> 00:01:58.552
Now stop doing this by hand.

00:01:58.552 --> 00:02:01.178
The policy enables automatic growth up

00:02:01.178 --> 00:02:03.365
to a ceiling you choose,

00:02:03.365 --> 00:02:04.678
plus scheduled trims.

00:02:09.744 --> 00:02:10.416
Policy stored.

00:02:10.416 --> 00:02:12.434
The machine takes over from here.

00:02:15.697 --> 00:02:16.740
Read it back:

00:02:16.740 --> 00:02:17.435
auto-grow on,

00:02:17.435 --> 00:02:18.826
ceiling at eight gigabytes,

00:02:18.826 --> 00:02:20.216
trim on a schedule.

00:02:24.834 --> 00:02:25.774
Set once,

00:02:25.774 --> 00:02:26.715
forgotten safely.

00:02:30.011 --> 00:02:32.802
And the view that ties it together:

00:02:32.802 --> 00:02:35.193
storage health shows every repo's usage,

00:02:35.193 --> 00:02:35.991
the pool,

00:02:35.991 --> 00:02:38.781
and how much copy-on-write sharing is saving

00:02:38.781 --> 00:02:39.180
you.

00:02:39.180 --> 00:02:40.088
One view:

00:02:40.088 --> 00:02:40.542
usage,

00:02:40.542 --> 00:02:40.995
savings,

00:02:40.995 --> 00:02:42.811
and room to grow.

00:02:43.589 --> 00:02:46.196
And that's a wrap on the

00:02:46.196 --> 00:02:46.631
series!

00:02:46.631 --> 00:02:47.500
Eighteen tutorials,

00:02:47.500 --> 00:02:49.673
from install to autopilot storage.

00:02:49.673 --> 00:02:51.846
Your servers are yours again.

00:02:51.846 --> 00:02:53.150
Thanks for watching!
